description.plain:
“cellophane” was FKA twigs' comeback single – the first release as a solo artist since 2016’s “Good To Love”. It was the lead single for her second studio album, MAGDALENE, along with being the 9th and final track on the album.

FKA twigs had been sharing videos of her pole-dancing for months prior to “cellophane.” With the release of the song alongside the music video, her vision became clear. She mentioned that the visual idea that came during the writing process of the song could only be fulfilled by learning how to pole-dance.

At its core, “cellophane” comes across as a piano ballad over a sparse rhythm – part of which is beat-boxed. The word cellophane, a common packaging material, is used as a metaphor for the state of a relationship:

All wrapped in cellophane, the feelings that we had

annotations:
And I don’t want to have to share our love
 I try, but I get overwhelmed
This shows how Twigs is tired of sharing her love with the outside world and media, always wanting to see their relationship. She’s trying to make them happy, but she can’t do it.
And I just want to feel you’re there

twigs has reached such a stage of desperation that she isn’t even pleading for her lover to take any action on her part or publicly defend her against paparazzi. All she wants is for him to physically be near, and that would be enough for her.

Didn’t I do it for you?
 Why don’t I do it for you?
 Why won’t you do it for me
 When all I do is for you?

Accompanied solely by an atmospheric piano, twigs opens the delicate track by speaking directly to her former lover. The lines reveal twigs in a vulnerable and anguished state, begging to know why her lover didn’t feel the same way for her as she did for him.

twigs spoke with i-D Magazine about her ironic perception of these opening lines, saying:

It’s funny that, as women, we’re asking those questions [“Didn’t I do it for you? / Why don’t I do it for you?”] without realising how epic and iconic we are. Those feelings I had are the result of some socially brainwashed upbringing that I’m not even aware of, but actually, in the core of myself, I know that I’m fine. It’s like a duality. From when I made the song to when I made the video, my perspective on who I was had changed as well. I just knew it was gonna be okay.

They’re waiting
 They’re watching
 They’re watching us
 They’re hating
 They’re waiting
 And hoping
 I’m not enough

This again refers to the pressure she had from racists, who consistently undermined her and called her ugly. She refers to the fact that those critics waited and watched for her to ‘mess up’ in the relationship to prove that she wasn’t a good partner for him.

They wanna see us, wanna see us alone
 They wanna see us, wanna see us apart
 They wanna see us, wanna see us alone
 They wanna see us, wanna see us apart

twigs received incessant criticism for her relationship with actor Robert Pattinson, mainly from fans who were angry that Pattinson didn’t end up with his white Twilight co-star Kristen Stewart.

During an interview with New York Times in 2015, twigs commented on how the criticism and backlash affected her, saying:

It’s really hard — I can’t begin to explain how awful it is. It makes you want to just stop everything sometimes. It makes you want to smash your face into the mirror.

Many opposers to the relationship often used twigs' biracial background as a way to target her, too. twigs followed up by saying:

There’s no amount of songs I can sing or dances I can dance that will prove to them I’m not a monkey. Nothing can impale my work or make me choose not to say things a certain way or make an image the way I want.

In the end, the criticism drove twigs and Pattinson to split in 2017, sparking the inspiration for MAGDALENE.
And I don’t want to have to share our love
There is a third person in the relationship between FKA Twigs and her lover, the media and the outside world, always looking in and wanting to take a piece of the relationship.
All wrapped in cellophane, the feelings that we had

Commonly known as plastic wrap, cellophane protects and preserves foods. The usage of the past tense suggests that their feelings for each other have been packaged and stored away, signifying the end of the relationship.

In the first few lines, she says she doesn’t want to share their love – she doesn’t like that their relationship is on display to the public.

Although wrapped in cellophane, their relationship is still vulnerable to media scruntity under the thin transparent material.

Their feelings and relationship remain exposed – shared with those who think she’s not enough.

annotations: Higher than a motherfucker, dreaming of you as my lover (Mouth open, you’re high)

In this lyric, FKA uses the word high as a triple entendre:


For a start, FKA is currently “high” off the love of her boyfriend. She enjoys fantasizing sexual intercourse with him.
This also refers to her celebrity status, and her boyfriend’s ordinance in contrast to it. This is ironic, due to the fact that most ordinary people fall in love with celebrities, instead of vice versa.
Finally, twigs could actually be high off of drugs as she sings these lyrics. Even though she has never been confirmed to be on drugs, it is always a possibility.



This theme also continues within the next lyric, as it refers to “flying like a streamer”.
Mouth open, you’re high

This continues on this triple entendre.

An orgasm or pleasure in general is normally accompanied by opening the mouth as a sign of satisfaction.
It continues the drug metaphor–he is high on her seduction.
This is also likely a reference to oral sex.
Pull out the incisor, give me two weeks, you won’t recognise her

Incisors are teeth that are adapted for cutting. twigs is urging him to pull out of his current partner’s “bite,” or her hold on him.
She claims two weeks will be enough to blow his mind with all she has to offer, and he will forget about his ex.
￼

Flying like a streamer, thinking of new ways to do each other
 (Mouth open, you’re high)

Streamers, like those used as party decorations or in ribbon dancing (shown below), are paper-thin and move or “fly” easily in the wind.
The themes of the song are clearly continued in this line as “flying” plays off of the “high” wordplay twigs uses throughout and “do each other” continues the sexual release.
Twigs, who used to be a dancer, often dances onstage during her concerts. She sometimes performs this song while swirling a mass of diaphanous fabric above and around her, as she did during her Congregata performance. This is a clear reference to the line “flying like a streamer” as well as a beautiful visual element.
High motherfucker, get your mouth open, you know you’re mine

Twigs is referring to herself as a drug that is capable of healing her crush’s pain or troubles. Instead of resisting, she tells him to open his mouth and breathe her drug in because he knows deep down he’s hers.

I know it hurts, you know, I’d put you first
 (I can fuck you better than her)

Twigs claims that she has better qualities than her ex’s  current girlfriend – namely, she is more sexually experienced and adept. Though she understands that it’s painful for him to leave the girl he’s with, twigs thinks he’ll be better off with someone who can satisfy him more. “I can fuck you better than her” is essentially the thesis statement of the song.
You say you’re lonely, I say you’ll think about it

Even though this boy is already in a relationship, the temptation to have sex with a girl as beautiful as FKA is intense. Twigs is attempting to use her power of persuasion to seduce this boy.

This also could be a play on the word “head”, which is a reference to oral sex. The themes of body parts appear throughout the song.
Flying like a streamer, thinking of new ways to do each other
It’s interesting to note how far she has come since “Papi Pacify” where she was practically begging her boyfriend to love her.

Unless you’re the only one who instigates
 Get your mouth open, you’re high

Twigs desperately wants this man to stop avoiding her and his obvious attraction to her, and start initiating passion between them. She is ready for the sex.

She’s not going to stick around if he can’t start taking responsibility for his half of the relationship. He needs to be fully dedicated to her, and give up his other lover. And he has to be the one to do it on his own–she doesn’t want to have to drag him away screaming.
You say you want me, I say you’ll live without it
She’s having a power trip. She’s finally in a position where she can play hard to get because of her level of confidence.

description.plain:
On “oh my love,” twigs explores a relationship where she wants more than what the guy wants. Struggling between taking his lead and keeping it casual, a waste of time for her, or taking action like getting into another relationship or speaking up.

In keeping with the theme of community that the mixtape explores, the track features a spoken intro and outro from two of twigs' close friends, Suzannah Pettigrew and Abigail Sakari, respectively. While Pettigrew rants about a hard-to-read and indecisive fling, Sakari closes the track by reminding twigs, as well as those listening, that her worth and success is not dictated by flakey men in her life.

description.plain:
“killer” was first previewed on FKA twigs' TikTok on June 4th, 2022, where she’s seen kissing Elite actor Arón Piper for the music video released on July 20th, 2022.

The song follows twigs making her way through the love world and reflecting upon her previous relationships, ones of infatuation where she would lie to herself to make it work.

2013’s “Papi Pacify” similarly explores toxic relationships, and the recurring theme of denial in love is one seen throughout her 2019 album, MAGDALENE.

annotations: Didn’t wanna call it

In this lyric, FKA Twigs uses the lyric didn’t wanna call it as a double entendre:


Physicians often prompt hospital residents to declare a patient’s time of death by saying, “Call it.” Though she knows the relationship is over, she doesn’t want to officially end it.
Oftentimes, victims of intimate partner violence will subconsciously ignore red flags due to cognitive dissonance. She continued the relationship because it was difficult to believe someone who claimed to love her was also capable of hurting her.

annotations: Cuts in her arm, here I go, make secrets

With the ‘'cuts in her arm’‘ Lean introduces us to the girl he’s going to spend time with, who leads a crazy and suffering life from which she sees no way out, just like he does with his own (’‘I’m really stuck here, I can’t escape’‘).
The song’s main theme is developed in the great desire, joy (BLISS), excitement and relief even, to be able to leave behind all the sadness sharing time (’‘make secrets’‘) with the other person and giving everything when you are with that one
Peace in my song, war in my head
Reference to the post warlord era
Pauly D the way I live my lifestyle
Paula D was a cast member on the reality show Jersey Shore known for having a wild lifestyle

Room 654, meet me at the hotel (You said you’d meet me at the hotel)
 I be in and out, but I’m going in the bliss (Bliss on bliss on bliss on)

Possibly to do with the angel number 654.
If twigs took any part in writing, she tends to explore spirituality. 654 carries the meaning of breaking habits and patterns of behaviour.
This idea is furthered by the lyric “I be in and out” as the habit she intends on breaking isn’t ‘bliss’. Rather it’s the “little company” that she manifests to be good for her in the chorus.
Sniffing glue and I’m seeing sounds
N.E.R.D reference‼️‼️‼️‼️😱😱😱😱😱
Like The Exorcist, I’m making heads spin again
A reference to the movie “The exorcist” from 1973 where the 12-year old daughter who’s possessed by a demon spins her head
Outro: FKA twigs, Yung Lean, & Mapei

The song’s outro features additional vocals from Mapei, who is part of the collective MOR alongside Fredrik Okazaki.

On April 8, 2022, the artist herself confirmed her involvement on the mixtape, being the voice behind the “Stardust” and “You are now listening to Yung Lean” tags, via an Instagram post.

The key and the gate, it’s a Leanworld
 And I’m the kingdom all night, got the key, girl

Yung Lean opens his first verse with what most likely represents a reference to his 2014 song “Leanworld,”, where he sang similar lines:

The key and the gate, it’s a Leanworld
Heavenly Kingdom with a lean girl
And the city still blue, yeah, like the summer was
A reference to producer Woesum’s 2021 album “Blue Summer.” Woesum is a friend of Lean. He helped produce tracks on Stardust. Lean was also featured on Blue Summer.

She teased a snippet of “ride the dragon” by sharing choreography of the then-unknown track on January 10th via her Instagram, confirming the track the next day on another Instagram post with a CDQ snippet, and a final snippet on the 12th.

annotations: I’m still that mysterious bitch

twigs has always kept an air of mystery to her throughout the years, an ethereal presence. Here she shows that, whilst this mixtape is a step in a different direction from her previous works, she is still the girl she was before

Cause I’ve been skipping through the city
 Feeling pretty with nobody to get on
 So if you really wanna kiss me
 Do it quickly ’fore the end of the song
 Waiting a minute for your love

In May of 2022 Twigs shared the meaning of this lyric via instagram stories writing the following.

“the ride the dragon caprivid is a video that’s very close to my heart because it is filmed in my local area, on the steps of my local town hall which is where the community go to vote and it’s also next to the theatre that i’ve gone to see lots of local productions in over the years. it’s really the epitome of my experience growing up in London, choreographing things with my friends and going and shooting around Stratford or in Maryland and just doing choreo and filming it on the street. run and gun, let’s just get it done and look cute.
‘“cause i’ve been skipping through the city
feeling pretty with nobody to get on
so if you really wanna kiss me
do it quickly 'fore the end of the song
waiting a minute for your love'”
Ride the dragon

“riding the dragon” is slang for achieving a high, usually through heroin. by using this phrase to describe her attraction to and desire for this person, fka twigs demonstrates how euphoric, addictive, and possibly toxic being with this person is.

(Think about you, ’bout you all week)
 Hey, I made you a mixtape
 (Work hard, get my body, body lean)
 Because when I feel you, I feel me
 (Love plays, called hide and seek)
 And when I feel me, it feels good

FKA twigs posted these lyrics alongside the official announcement of CAPRISONGS on January 6th, 2022. While twigs has 2 albums and 3 EPs, CAPRISONGS serves as her first mixtape, which boasts the most features she’s ever had on a project:

All working with people I’ve never worked with before. I’ve got more collaborations and features on this album than I’ve ever had before. The majority of the people I’ve never met in real life. We spent a lot of time with each other over FaceTime. It’s a real product of 2020.
